  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions spans several decades and involves international cooperation to combat financial crimes. Here's an overview:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Historically, financial crimes and concealment of illicit funds existed\n- No comprehensive legal frameworks specifically targeting money laundering\n\n2. Initial Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Developments:\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (United States) - First significant legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Milestones:\n- 1989 - Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n- Created 40 Recommendations for global AML strategies\n\n4. Key Legislative Periods:\n- 1980s: Growing recognition of money laundering as a serious crime\n- 1990s: Enhanced international legal frameworks\n- 2001: USA PATRIOT Act significantly expanded AML regulations\n\n5. Major Focus Areas:\n- Detecting illegal financial transactions\n- Preventing terrorist financing\n- Tracking proceeds from drug trafficking\n- Establishing reporting mechanisms\n- Implementing international cooperation protocols\n\nThe legal framework continues evolving to address emerging financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
